The FDA has granted 3 EUA's as of 03/02/21. The EUA process from filing an application to approval by the FDA took 18 days for Moderna and 22 days for Pfizer, and J&J. AstraZeneca and Novovax are the next two most likely companies to seek an EUA from the FDA. The AstaZeneca vaccine has received approval from several other countries and is being widely administered in Europe, Mexico, India, Argentina, and several other countries. However, AstraZeneca has faced problems with its data related to the efficaciousness in the elderly population and their mistakes in dosing their trials. As a result, AstraZeneca will likely have to wait to conclude US phase 3 trials which will take a few more weeks. Novovax's vaccine results from Britain look excellent. Novovax will likely seek British approval in the next few weeks based on these trials conducted there. Then, Novovax is expected to apply for US approval in the 2nd quarter of 2021 based on the British trial data (if FDA will accept it), or it will wait on US phase 3 trials to complete, which could take 2-3 more months. It is unlikely that AstraZeneca or Novovax will receive EUA approval before 3/31/21 as that would require filing an EUA application no later than March 13, 2021, based on recent precedent. With that said, as variants continue to spread and the decline in positive cases and hospitalizations stalls in the U.S., it is possible that a 4th vaccine could receive an EUA in the next 29 days.

As a reference point, J&J completed their Covid Phase III trial in mid-December 2020. It then took them a little over a month to fully compile the data, and a few days for submission for FDA approval. Novavax has not completed phase III (2/27/21).

The FDA says it is working "rapidly" toward approval of the J&J vaccine, making it the third.[1] The Washington Post says it could be as early as this weekend (February 27-28).[2] Of the two vaccine makers that appear to be looking for US EUA, Novavax and Astrazenca, both of which received Operation Warp Speed funding, both appear to be waiting on phase III data. The Novavax website says only that they will be releasing phase III trial data during "Q1 2021" which does not seem promising to be the fourth approved for EUA by March 31.[3] Astrazenca has no indications on their website and a spokesperson told the media only that they are in on-going contact with FDA. The problems with the clinical trials for Astrazenca seem to be creating incentives for the FDA to be especially careful now that we seem to have three vaccines.

There are currently 5 vaccines associated with the FDA(either Operation Warp Speed-funded or a "fast track" designation) that are in or nearing phase 3 trials. Of those, Pfizer and Moderna have already applied for approval, which, according to most sources, should be granted by the end of December. The AstraZeneca vaccine is the next closest. They are reporting results from phase 3 trials, and even though a study error led to some unexpected good outcomes, the vaccine is still safe and meets efficacy thresholds, so it will likely be approved. The Johnson & Johnson vaccine started phase 3 trials at the end of September. Based on the trial length for the other vaccines (~6 mo), this vaccine is on the cusp of meeting a 31 March timeline for trial completion and approval. All other vaccine candidates are on later timelines. https://www.raps.org/news-and-articles/news-articles/2020/3/covid-19-vaccine-tracker
